👉 Creating Your Own Java Documentation

Java Documentation is great!
It helps us get info about what method/class/Entity to use when.

We can create our own package i.e. Documentation in Java

JavaDoc tool
javadoc command allows us to create documentation in HTML format for our own package.
Java provides tags for class or package to assist with the java doc generation

👉 Tags for class or a package : ©️

@author : Used to specify author name. 
@version : Adds the version
@Since : to add when this version written
@param : Describes method parameters.

👉 Example

/**
 * This class demonstrates JavaDoc tags
 * @author Rahul
 * @version 1.0
 * @since 2025
 */

public class Demo {

    /**
     * Adds two integers
     * @param a first number
     * @param b second number
     * @return sum of a and b
     */

    public int add(int a, int b){
        return a + b;
    }

    /**
     * Divides two numbers
     * @param a numerator
     * @param b denominator
     * @return division result
     * @throws ArithmeticException when b = 0
     */

    public int divide(int a, int b){
        return a / b;
    }
}

👉 How to Generate Documentation

Step 1: Save file
                  Demo.java
Step 2: Open Terminal / CMD
                  Run command : javadoc Demo.java                
Step 3: Generated Files
Java creates multiple HTML files including:
                  index.html
                  package pages
                  class pages

👉 How to Open Documentation

Open  :  index.html in browser.

You will see professional documentation similar to official Java docs.

👉 Advantages of JavaDoc

✔ Easy to understand code
✔ Professional documentation
✔ Helps other developers
✔ Useful for APIs and libraries
✔ Automatically generated HTML pages

👉 Difference Between Comments and JavaDoc
| Comments                | JavaDoc             |
| ----------------------- | ------------------- |
| For programmers         | For documentation   |
| Not generated into HTML | Converted into HTML |
| Uses `//` or `/* */`    | Uses `/** */`       |
